I have a long-running process which uses pyroute2. To clalify it, do I have to do as follows ?

### For Single-thread environment.

```
from pyroute2 import IPDB

class SimpleManager(object):

    def __init__(self, ipdb_kwargs=None):
        self._ipdb_kwargs = ipdb_kwargs or {}

    @property
    def ipdb(self):
        try:
            return self._ipdb
        except AttributeError:
            ipdb = self._ipdb = IPDB(**self._ipdb_kwargs)
            return ipdb

    def get_routes(self, ipdb_kwargs=None):
        with self.ipdb as ipdb:
            routes = ipdb.routes
            return {
                dst: routes[dst].dump()
                for dst in routes.keys()
            }

m = SimpleManager()
for i in range(10):
    r = m.get_routes()
    print('{}: OK'.format(i))
```

#### For multi-threads environment
In case that many child threads use IPDB.
```
from pyroute2 import IPDB
import threading
from Queue import LifoQueue

class ThreadSafeManager(object):

    def __init__(self, num_of_ipdb=3, ipdb_kwargs=None):
        q = self._ipdb_q = LifoQueue(maxsize=num_of_ipdb)
        for i in range(num_of_ipdb):
            q.put(IPDB(**(ipdb_kwargs or {})))

    def get_routes(self, ipdb_kwargs=None):
        ipdb = self._ipdb_q.get()
        try:
            with ipdb:
                routes = ipdb.routes
                return {
                    dst: routes[dst].dump()
                    for dst in routes.keys()
                }
        finally:
            self._ipdb_q.put(ipdb)

m = ThreadSafeManager()
threads = []
for i in range(10):
    t=threading.Thread(target=m.get_routes)
    t.start()
    threads.append(t)

for t in threads:
    t.join()
```

Hmm, I'm not sure why `addRows` isn't working for you... I [know it works](https://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/example-add-rows.html).

Are you still using the pager? The [`removeRows` option](https://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#pager-removerows) is a pager option and should be added to either the pager function call:

```js
$table.tablesorterPager({
  // target the pager markup - see the HTML block below
  container: $pager,
  size: 10,
  removeRows: true
});
```

Or, if you're using the widget, add it to the `widgetOptions` as `pager_removeRows`:

```js
$table.tablesorter({
  // ...
  widgetOptions: {
    pager_removeRows: true,
    pager_selectors: {
      container: $pager
    },
    pager_size: 10,
    // ...
  }
});
```

Hi @raviankam525!

From looking at that code, it appears that the "any" match filter is being set.

You can combine filter types if you only want exact AND matches: `'{q}" AND {q}"`

[Here is a demo](http://jsfiddle.net/856bzzeL/674/)

Please note that you will not be able to match cells that contain any spaces... trying to find "Aaron Johnson Sr Esq" will not return any results because the default filter breaks up the query at every space. So the filter widget would be looking for "Aaron AND Johnson AND Sr AND Esq" exact matches. Internally, it creates a regex for each query that becomes `/^(Aaron)$/i`, `/^(Johnson)$/i`, `/^(Sr)$/i` and `/^(Esq)$/i`.

If you want to change the way the query is being split, you'll need to change the regular expression after the filter widget initializes:

```js
$('table').tablesorter({
  // other options
  initialized: function( table ) {
    // this is the default regex, it is created upon initialization and is dependent
    // on the $.tablesorter.language.and setting (default is "and")
    $.tablesorter.filter.regex.andSplit = /(?:\s+(?:and|&&)\s+)/gi
  }
});

Hi @yogini16!

I created [this demo](http://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/856bzzeL/801/) and the time column sorts as expected.

The range column data was modified so that the start time includes the time of day ("AM" or "PM"), and requires the following code & parser to work:

```js
$(function() {
  $.tablesorter.addParser({
    id: 'time-range',
    is: function(str) {
      return false;
    },
    format: function(str, table) {
      // isolate time... ignore month, day and year
      var temp, s, e,
        times = [],
        timeParts = (str || '').match(/([1-9]|1[0-2]):([0-5]\d)(\s[AP]M)|((?:[01]\d|[2][0-4]):[0-5]\d)/gi);
      if (timeParts && timeParts.length === 2) {
        s = new Date('2000/01/01 ' + (timeParts[0] || ''));
        e = new Date('2000/01/01 ' + (timeParts[1] || ''));
      }
      times[0] = s instanceof Date && isFinite(s) ? s.getTime() : '';
      times[1] = e instanceof Date && isFinite(e) ? e.getTime() : '';
      return times.join(' - ');
    },
    type: 'text'
  });

  $('table').tablesorter({
    // debug:true,
    theme: 'blue',
    widgets: ['zebra']
  });
});
```

Also, please note the class name in the header:

```html
<th class="sorter-time-range">Time Frame</th>
```

Sadly that parser won't work because if an `href` is defined, it saves the cache value as `1`, so the sort will look like it gets stuck. Also, it's set to "numeric" so even if a string was returned, string values become zero (i.e. `parseFloat('foo') // 0`)

Try this parser instead ([demo](http://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/856bzzeL/601/)):

```js
// Custom parser for parsing Href values
$.tablesorter.addParser({
    id: "href",
    is: function () {
        return false;
    },
    format: function (s, table, cell) {
        var href = $(cell).find('a').attr('href') || '',
            // replace protocol
            result = $.trim( href.replace(/(https?|ftp|file):\/\//, '' ) );
        return result || s;
    },
    parsed: true, // filter widget flag
    type: "text"
});
```

I copied the `replace` function from the "url" parser because "http" and "https" should be ignored while sorting.

Hi @darkred!

I think the problem is that sugar.js modifies the prototype and was causing a javascript error. I did the following:

* Switch to using [date.js](http://www.datejs.com/), which accepts "min" and "sec" so you don't need to modify those strings. But you do need to convert "hr" into "hour".
* jQuery is already available on the page, so I removed the `@require`
* Included the datejs parser inline and modified it to replace "hr" with "hour". Removed that `@require`.
* Added `@run-at document-idle`

And it started working:

```js
// ==UserScript==
// @name        ixIRC - make search results sortable
// @include     https://www.ixirc.com/?q=*
// @grant       none
// @run-at      document-idle
// @require     https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/jquery.tablesorter/2.28.10/js/jquery.tablesorter.min.js
// @require     https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/datejs/1.0/date.min.js
// ==/UserScript==
(() => {
 // jQuery fix for tables lacking a thead / http://aaron.jorb.in/blog/2010/03/jquery-fix-for-tables-lacking-a-thead/
 $('#results-table').prepend($('<thead></thead>').append($('#results-table tr:first').remove()));

 $.tablesorter.addParser({
  id: "datejs",
  is: function() {
   return false;
  },
  format: function(s) {
   var str = s.replace('hr', 'hour');
   var date = Date.parse ? Date.parse(str) : s ? new Date(str) : s;
   return date instanceof Date && isFinite(date) ? date.getTime() : s;
  },
  type: "numeric"
 });

 // http://stackoverflow.com/a/26343716/3231411
 $('#results-table').tablesorter ({
  headers: {
   7: { sorter:'datejs'},
   8: { sorter:'datejs'}
  }
 });

})();
```

