Webpack has a concept of entry points, which lets you build multiple bundles, and also lets you have multiple configs at once.
The idea is that you create one config and entry point for the client side, and a different config for the server side.

_webpack.config.js:_
```js
module.exports = [{
    // Server side config
    entry: {
        ComponentOne: ['./src/ComponentOne.jsx'],
        ComponentTwo: ['./src/ComponentTwo.jsx'],
    },
    output: {
        libraryTarget: 'commonjs2',
        filename: '[name].server.js',
        ... etc ...
    },
    ... etc ...
},
{
    // Client side config
    entry: {
      main: ['./src/main.jsx'],
    },
    ... etc ...
}
```

The server side entry point should just be the react component itself, whereas the client side one will probably be a bootstrap function.

Then you give `render_component` the path to the built file `ComponentOne.server.js`.

